Package and Data

For this assignment, we have two packages to load: tidyverse and nycflights13. You should be familiar by now with the first package tidyverse. The second package is for the flights data set were using for the assignment: Flights that Departed NYC in 2013 (see https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/nycflights13/versions/1.0.1 for details). The below code chunk is to load these packages and take a look at the data set.

library(tidyverse)
library(nycflights13)

  • Q1-1. Remove the columns year from your data frame (flights) [Hint: select()]

  • Q1-2. Add a new variable, total_delay, which is the sum of dep_delay and arr_delay, and sort your data frame in descending order of total_delay. Save the output as a new data frame flight1
flights1 <- flights %>%
  mutate(total_delay = dep_delay + arr_delay) %>% 
  arrange(desc(total_delay))
  • Q1-3. Use flight1 data frame to draw box plots of total delay separately by carriers
ggplot(flights1, aes(x=carrier, y=total_delay)) + 
  geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Removed 9430 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

  • Q1-4. Use flights1 data frame and visualize the relationship between total delay time and flight distance. [Hint: ggplot and geom_point]
ggplot(flights1, aes(x=distance, y=total_delay)) + 
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 9430 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Question 2 - Which airline carrier is the most frequently delayed?

  • Q2-1. Filter flights whose dep_delay or arr_delay is greater than 60, and save it as a new data major_delay
major_delay <- flights %>%
  filter(dep_delay > 60 | arr_delay > 60)
  • Q2-2. Use major_delay data frame to create a frequency table of delayed flights by carrier, and save it as a new data frame carrier_table [Hint: count()]
carrier_table <- major_delay %>% 
  count(carrier)
  • Q2-3. Use carrier_table to draw a pie chart to examine the most frequently delayed carrier [Hint: set x="" and y=n]
ggplot(carrier_table, aes(x="", y=n, fill = carrier)) +
  geom_col() + 
  coord_polar("y", start=0)

Question 3 - JFK-departed flights

  • Q3-1. Filter flights that departed from JFK airport and save it as JFK_flights
JFK_flights <- flights %>%
  filter(origin=="JFK")
  • Q3-2. Use JFK_flights to create the histogram of departure delay (dep_delay) of flights that departed from JFK.
ggplot(JFK_flights, aes(x=dep_delay)) + 
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 1863 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

  • Q3-3. Use JFK_flights to create a frequency table of flight counts by destination.
dest_table<-JFK_flights %>% 
  count(dest) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))
  • Q3-4. Use dest_table to visualize the number of flights by destination, in decreasing order, that departed from JFK [Hint: try both geom_col() and geom_bar() see if which one would suit better. reorder()]
ggplot(dest_table, aes(x=reorder(dest, -n), y=n)) + 
  geom_col()

Question 4 - Which airline carrier is the most frequently departed from each of the NYC airports?

  • Q4-1. Group flights by (origin, carrier) and count the number of flights for each group [Hint: use group_by() and summarize()]
flights %>%
  group_by(origin, carrier) %>%
  summarize(n=n())

count_flights <- flights %>% 
  count(origin, carrier)
  • Q4-3. Use count_flights to draw the point plots of the number of flights by carrier (i.e., x-axis: carrier and y-axis: n) and change colors by carrier [Hint: geom_point()]
ggplot(count_flights, aes(x=carrier, y=n, color=carrier)) + 
  geom_point()

  • Q4-4. Separate the above plot by origin, and label x-axis as Carrier for each origin airport and y-axis as Frequency [Hint: use facet_wrap() or facet_grid()]
ggplot(count_flights, aes(x=carrier, y=n, color=carrier)) + 
  geom_point() +
  labs(x="Carrier for each origin airport", y="Frequency") + 
  facet_wrap(.~origin)
